        <table>
          <tr><th>Concept</th><th>One-liner answer</th></tr>
          <tr><td>git pull vs git fetch</td><td class="note">pull = fetch + merge. fetch downloads without touching your working branch.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>merge vs rebase</td><td class="note">merge = preserves full history with merge commit. rebase = linear history by replaying commits. Never rebase shared branches.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>reset --soft vs --hard</td><td class="note">soft = undo commit, keep staged. hard = undo commit + discard all changes. Dangerous.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>reset vs revert</td><td class="note">reset = rewrite history (local only). revert = new commit that undoes (safe for shared branches).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>HEAD</td><td class="note">Pointer to the current commit you're on. HEAD~1 = one commit back.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Fast-forward merge</td><td class="note">No divergence — Git simply moves the pointer forward. No merge commit created.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Detached HEAD state</td><td class="note">Checked out a commit hash directly, not a branch. Create a branch to save work.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>git flow vs trunk-based</td><td class="note">git flow = long-lived feature branches. Trunk-based = short-lived branches, merge to main daily.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>hard link vs soft link (Git)</td><td class="note">Not Git-specific — but .git uses hard links for pack files. Interview may confuse with Linux.</td></tr>
