          <table>
            <tr><th>Concept</th><th>One-liner answer</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Declarative vs Scripted</td><td class="note">Declarative = structured, strict, beginner-friendly. Scripted = full Groovy, flexible, legacy.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Jenkinsfile benefit</td><td class="note">Lives in your repo → version-controlled, reviewable, reproducible CI/CD config.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Why not build on master?</td><td class="note">Load + security risk. Heavy builds crash master → all jobs fail. Use dedicated agents.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Webhook vs polling</td><td class="note">Webhook = GitHub pushes to Jenkins (instant). Polling = Jenkins checks GitHub (slow, wasteful).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>parallel stages use case</td><td class="note">Run independent tests, scans, or builds simultaneously to reduce total pipeline time.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>input step use case</td><td class="note">Manual approval before prod deploy. Pauses pipeline until a human approves.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Shared library</td><td class="note">Reusable Groovy code stored in a Git repo. Multiple Jenkinsfiles import and call it. DRY pipelines.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Multibranch pipeline</td><td class="note">Automatically discovers all branches in a repo and creates a pipeline job for each one.</td></tr>
          </table>
        </div>
